WikifierOutput.InputText: Day length, or length of day, or length of daytime, refers to the temporal length of a day, or 24 hours, during which there is daylight. Due to the diffusion and refraction of sunlight by the atmosphere , there is actually daylight even when the sun is slightly below the horizon . Theoretically, the day length can be computed from the moment the upper limb of the sun 's disk appears on the horizon during sunrise to the moment when the upper limb disappears at the horizon during sunset . More conveniently, however, the center of the sun is often used in place of the upper limb for computing the day length. When sunrise and sunset do occur, the day length can be computed as 2ω sub o /sub /15 , where ω sub o /sub is the sunset hour angle in degrees ( ) given by the sunset equation . When sunrise and sunset do not occur during the course of a day, the day length is either 0 or 24 hours. To considerable accuracy, all the points at the same latitude on the same calendar date can be considered to have the same day length. The contour plot in the figure is computed using the sunset equation .
